In the heart of Shaw/Logan circle northwest D.C. stands a lively restaurant and lounge with so much tradition and a ambiance that makes you feel you stepped into Addis Ababa. The scent of frankenscence makes the room come alive and the environment itself is just full of love. Allow me to get to get started with the food. I ordered a combination plate for 1 just for starts. At $16 dollars, frankly... It is worth every penny. The Injera is fluffy and the vegetables make you feel so good inside in this age of covid. The doro wat, What?!? That is the best I've ever tasted in over a long time. The Gomen Kitfo, legendary. The whole dish and restaurant is a experience I hope and pray they need to go and try them out. They put their hearts into this, and I can see, feel, taste and understand it.

If you order take out, their portions are much smaller then what I've gotten from other Ethiopian restaurants for the price. The lega tibs were also dry/not what I'm use to getting. The cashier also pushed the injera into the take out container with her bare finger (bothered me, might not bother others). This place isn't the worst option but it's definitely not the best in the DMV area.

The restaurant is very casual and offers indoor and covered outdoor seating. You'll find all the Ethiopian dishes you'd desire and they are brought out quickly. The food quality and flavor is consistent and as good as any other Ethiopian restaurant I've tried in DC. Staff members are friendly and attentive. Lalibela is a great option for an informal, casual dinner with friends or a late night craving for Ethiopian.

I came here on a weekend for lunch and it was pretty great! We shared the two-person combo platter which had collard greens, yellow lentils, cabbage and carrots, beef, lamb, and chicken/egg. Everything was tasty but the flavors were a bit on the lighter side, and the injera (which came as one big piece per person which was unique) wasn't as sour as usual and I liked that. The food also wasn't super oily which I appreciated (but could also explain why the flavors weren't as strong). Selection was per usual of Ethiopian places. Prices were fair, the two-person combo was $28 pre-tax ($30.80 post-tax) which is about the same as other Ethiopian places. Quite an average Ethiopian place, and the ambiance was alright - the inside had a lot of TV screens with sports and service was average.

3.5 stars! Recently, I learned that DC has the second highest Ethiopian population in the world. That only means one thing - legit finger grubbing! No wonder every Groupon, Livingsocial, Amazon, all the coupons you can imagine offered Ethiopian as one of their most popular dining deals!  We were just exploring the neighborhood, got hungry, and decided to give Lalibela a try. We had a choice of either eating outdoor by the sidewalk which I later learned aka eaten alive by mosquito or indoor smokey, incensed dining. We went with the sidewalk and were immediately seated. The service was a bit slower but our foods were served promptly. 2 of us got the veggie platter, my husband got the meat sampler for 1, and I went with the veggie platter with fish.  Overall, we were impressed by our dishes. This was my third time having Ethiopian and I must say it had convinced me to crave/want more! All the veggies and meats were delicious. The (unlimited) injera soaked up all the stews nicely!  In addition, I wasn't expecting a whole fish to be presented on the side  (just $4 more than a regular veggie platter). It was fresh, hot, crispy, and meaty!  With so many Ethiopian options available in DC, I can't say I would be dying to return to Lalibela any time soon but definitely recommend others to at least give it a try!

Ordered take out, but I still enjoyed the experience. The wait staff is friendly and helpful. I ordered a beer while I waited and the bartender informed me on happy hour. I got 2 imports for 4.75!  Vest happy hour desk I've ever got. Incense was burning and the environment was relaxing and warm. I love Ethiopian food and I recommend this spot as a cool spot to come to when you're on the lo...
